## THE PROBLEM WITH SOCIOLOGY

Sociology has produced extraordinary observers. Durkheim mapped anomie. Marx traced the kinetic chain from modes of production to social conflict. Weber documented the rationalization of modernity. Wilson connected social behavior to evolutionary biology. Each built a powerful lens for examining specific aspects of social reality.

None built the instrument that makes all lenses comparable.

The failure is not empirical. Sociologists have accumulated enormous quantities of careful observation. The failure is foundational. Sociology developed without a substrate-neutral mathematical language capable of describing any social system at any scale using the same set of measurable quantities. Without such a language every social theory becomes an ideology — a set of observations true within its own frame of reference and untranslatable into any other.

The result is the tower of confusion that every student of sociology encounters. Gemeinschaft and Gesellschaft. Base and superstructure. Iron cage and Protestant ethic. Manifest and latent function. Each framework generates its own lexicon, its own research program, its own political commitments. The student must choose a tribe. The scientist cannot choose at all — because science requires a common measurement framework that does not yet exist.

**This theory provides that framework.**

The instrument is thermodynamics — the branch of physics that describes how energy flows through systems, how entropy is generated, how steady states are maintained, and how systems transition from one state to another. Thermodynamics is substrate-neutral. Its laws apply to gas molecules, to ecosystems, to economies, and to societies with equal precision. It provides the universal measurement language that sociology has always needed and never had.

What follows is the formal statement of the General Theory of Social Behavior — the application of thermodynamic principles to social systems at every scale from the individual organism to the planetary civilization.

