## SECTION 1 — THE ONTOLOGICAL FOUNDATION

### 1.1 The Universal Set and Social Sets

**Definition 1:** There is one and only one all-comprehensive set, defined to be the Universal Set {U}, which contains all forms of matter, energy, information, and entropy whether visible or invisible, measurable or hypothesized.

**Definition 2:** A Social Set {S} is a mathematically defined subset of {U} containing elements called members that are related to each other through a common set of Social Interactions {SI}.

**Definition 3:** Any subdivision of a Social Set {S} is defined to be a Sub-Social Set {s} of {S} if and only if all elements of {s} exhibit a set of Social Interactions {SI'} that distinguish the elements of {s} from the members of {S}, such that the elements of {s} are defined by an augmented set of core interactions {SI + SI'}.

**Definition 4:** When an element of {S} cannot be broken down into smaller social components it is called an **elementary member**. When it can be broken down it is called a **non-elementary member** or **fundamental element**. A person is a non-elementary social system — a society of cells exhibiting biological social organization nested within larger social structures.

### 1.2 Population Types

