### 1.3 Physical Systems and Boundary Conditions

**Definition — Physical System:** A collection of elements isolated from the rest of the universal set by a series of boundary conditions that structurally define and at least partially isolate members of the set from the remainder of the physical universe.

**Boundary mathematics:** When a system has multiple boundaries the number of boundaries is given by **b**ᵢⱼ where i, j represent the rows and columns of an (i × j) matrix. The total number of boundaries B equals the number of non-zero elements of the bᵢⱼ array.

**Nested systems:** When a physical system (A) is contained within the boundaries of a more comprehensive system (B), system (A) is defined to be a subsystem of (B) and is said to be nested within (B). If C ⊂ B ⊂ A, then A is defined to be a nested system N(A_BC) with a depth of two. The depth of a nested system equals the number of specified physical systems contained within its boundaries.

**Boundary permeability:** Boundaries exist on a spectrum from fully closed to fully open. A boundary is **mechanically penetrable** when a member can be made to penetrate it by the application of a force. The **critical force** is the magnitude at which the boundary-breaking force is sufficient to push a member through. The **percent closure** of a system is defined as:

```
% closure = (nᵢ - Δn) / nᵢ × 100

where nᵢ is the initial population density and Δn is the number of boundary crossings in interval Δt.
```

**Selective boundaries:** Boundaries that permit some elements to pass while blocking others are labeled **selective** or **porous**. Elements that can pass through boundaries that are coercive to other elements are said to be **boundary indifferent** with respect to those specific boundaries.

