One of the most important taxonomic innovations of this theory is the classification of social organisms by generational level — a framework that connects biological organization to social organization through a single continuous hierarchy.

**First Generation Living Systems:** Single-cell organisms — bacteria, amoebae, algae. The elementary social unit of biological organization.

**Second Generation Living Systems:** Multicellular organisms contained within a physical boundary. Any organism composed of two or more cells in integrated functional relationship.

