**Ecological Systems:** When various types of distinguishable first, second, and third generation organisms exist within a system and are interdependent upon one another for their survival, the system is defined to be an ecosystem.

**The Super-Organism Trajectory:** The evolutionary evidence suggests that third-generation social organisms, given sufficient time and favorable conditions, tend toward increasing integration — toward what can be described as a super-organism in which the individual components become as specialized and interdependent as the cells of a multicellular body. The social insects provide the clearest existing examples. The human species is at an early and critical stage of this trajectory.

