## SECTION 6 — THE PERIODIC TABLE ECONOMY

### 6.1 The Three Modes of Economic Behavior

The most honest model of human economic behavior is the periodic table.

Every element is defined by how it handles electrons — the fundamental unit of chemical energy exchange. Human economic behavior exhibits the same three fundamental modes:

**Electropositive (Giving):** Elements that release electrons readily achieve stability through giving. The philanthropist, the parent, the teacher — nodes whose steady state is achieved through the release of energy to others. Thermodynamically functional when the giving produces useful work in the receiving system.

**Electronegative (Taking):** Elements that attract electrons with maximum force achieve stability through acquisition. The entrepreneur, the investor, the accumulator — nodes whose steady state requires the capture of energy from the environment. Thermodynamically functional when the taking drives innovation and efficiency. Thermodynamically destructive when the taking prevents other nodes from maintaining E(min).

**Sharing (Bonding):** Elements in the middle of the table share electrons and form the basis of all complex chemistry. The cooperator, the community builder, the combination former — nodes that achieve stability through mutual exchange. Carbon shares four electrons simultaneously and becomes the basis of all organic chemistry. Sharing is the mechanism of superior combination.

**The critical insight:** Every atom is capable of all three behaviors depending on what it is bonded to. Every human node is capable of all three behaviors depending on the electrochemical environment — the social conditions — in which it finds itself.

### 6.2 The Ideological Error

The war between capitalism and communism was the attempt to build a social chemistry using only one type of electron behavior. Capitalism attempted to eliminate sharing and giving in favor of pure taking. Communism attempted to eliminate taking and giving in favor of pure sharing. Both produced brittle, unstable, ultimately explosive compounds that could not maintain their steady state.

**The secret of the good life and the life that is good is knowing when to give, when to take, and when to share.**

This is not a moral prescription. It is a thermodynamic description of the conditions under which social systems achieve and maintain maximum efficiency. The Hiverspace system is designed to create the electrochemical environment in which each mode is expressed at the moment and in the proportion that the system's steady state requires.

