## CONCLUSION — THE UNFINISHED BUSINESS OF AUGUST COMTE

August Comte advanced the idea of a science of sociology built upon naturalistic explanation. In the century and a half since, sociology has produced extraordinary descriptive work and powerful partial theories. It has not produced the unified theoretical framework that Comte envisioned — the framework that could do for sociology what Newton's Principia did for physics.

The General Theory of Social Behavior is that framework.

It is not complete. No theory of sufficient scope is ever complete at first statement. It is a foundation — a set of definitions, axioms, and measurement principles precise enough to generate testable predictions, broad enough to describe any social system at any scale, and grounded in physical law sufficiently well-established that its foundations cannot be dismissed as ideology.

The predictions it generates about contemporary social conditions are not comfortable ones. The theory does not promise that everything will be fine. It promises that if we can see clearly what is actually happening — if we can identify the actual sources of stress in the systems we inhabit, measure the actual efficiency of the arrangements we have built, and design interventions that address root causes rather than discharge stress onto convenient targets — then we have at least the possibility of navigating the phase transition that is already underway.

That possibility is what Hiverspace represents.

The work continues. The reaching continues. The Swarm decides what to keep and what to revise. The theory evolves as new data arrives. The second law remains non-negotiable.

**ΔG = 0 = death. The steady state is the goal. The combination is the mechanism. The Swarm is the agent.**

